            {
               "text": "<p style=\"font-style: italic;\" id=\"htChinaZhongguo\"></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "### Where is the center?\n\nThe image in this section is present in the Kano collection of the Tohoku University Digital Archives (<htcite0>). It represents the Chinese understanding of the world, which, in the pages of *History Tracers*, is always presented with an explanation by Professor Xiaohuan Zhao, shown at the beginning of this text (<htcite1>). Depending on which part of the world you live in, it is very likely that China (Zhongguo 中國) is not what you understand to be the \"center of the world\"; it would possibly be the Greenwich Meridian (<htcite2>).\n\nThis understanding leads us to reflect:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "80851755-2574-4396-9d44-65853e30e59a",
                     "text": "Ricci, Matteo",
                     "page": "Kon'yo bankoku zenzu",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "66858370-a9e8-44a7-88e1-8a2f5a516905",
                     "text": "Xiaohuan Zhao",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9828a108-dfdf-4692-a819-18b690d4a629",
                     "text": "Raikar, S.P.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "12",
                        "day": "22"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: We divide starting from...</b><br /><br />How would you define the center of the planet?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Choosing the answer\n\nAlthough we have studied, in other texts, that the central point would be zero (<htcite0>; <htcite1>; <htcite2>), answering where the center of the planet lies involves the problem of where to place that zero.\n\nIf we wanted to place zero where our species originated, then that starting point would be Africa. However, this understanding was only possible with great scientific advances and is relatively recent (<htcite3>).\n\nDespite the knowledge that we originated in Africa—over 300 millennia ago—this led different peoples, such as France, Prussia, and the United Kingdom, to define their own reference points (<htcite4>).\n\nIn <htdate0>, representatives from 25 nations voted in Washington, D.C., United States, to define the Greenwich Meridian, which passes through Africa, as the prime meridian. However, they took a London observatory as a reference to name it, and we must note that France did not join the 22 voters in favor of this definition (<htcite5>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9618a83e-f232-49db-84f6-fc3455a3f1d1",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Drawing to count",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "92b5d15c-d26a-4ad9-82af-3262649cf2e4",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Walking Among the Numbers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b8c8840f-0631-420d-b5b3-7ebbebdb9625",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Integers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ab1dda1e-95c2-4087-8299-e851e58bdc6f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Humans",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
