                     "month": "",
                     "day": ""
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: That's all</b><br /><br />Were there only 25 nations in the world in <htdate0>?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1884",
                     "month": "",
                     "day": ""
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Unlike in <htdate0>, when not all nations were represented, today our prime meridian—the imaginary line that encircles the Earth—the International Reference Meridian, was approved by all countries and passes 102.5 meters (336 feet) from the old meridian used as a reference, the Airy Meridian, which was the fourth meridian created by the British (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9828a108-dfdf-4692-a819-18b690d4a629",
                     "text": "Raikar, S.P.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "12",
                        "day": "22"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1884",
                     "month": "",
                     "day": ""
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### A Central Idea\n\nAs we saw at the beginning of this text, China (Zhongguo 中國) has possessed the concept of being the center for about 3,000 years, and therefore, the definition initially established in <htdate0> simply did not take this millennial understanding into account.\n\nOn the other hand, when China (Zhongguo 中國) accepts the International Reference Meridian (<htcite0>), that does not cause the nation to change its identity.\n\nWhat appears to be a contradictory idea is, in fact, something already experienced for a few centuries by the Chinese and indicates a more general understanding. As can be observed in the map at the top of this section, made by the Jesuit Matteo Ricci while living among the Chinese, we have the 17th-century world, according to the Gregorian calendar, in which China (Zhongguo 中國) is at the center, possessing relevance analogous to that of Europe (<htcite1>).\n\nGiven this scenario, nothing has changed for China (Zhongguo 中國).\n\n#### Let us be centered\n\nMaps cannot be considered neutral elements (<htcite2>), however, we will try to do so. We invite the reader to observe the current map using the Mercator projection, as is generally done in Western books, in **Figure 2**:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9828a108-dfdf-4692-a819-18b690d4a629",
                     "text": "Raikar, S.P.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "12",
                        "day": "22"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "59b80e45-89fe-437f-b4b2-fc191b1e7d14",
                     "text": "Kästl, M.",
                     "page": "pp. 231- 234, 242 - 247",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "12",
                        "day": "22"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "59b80e45-89fe-437f-b4b2-fc191b1e7d14",
                     "text": "Kästl, M.",
                     "page": "pp. 242",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "12",
                        "day": "22"
                     }
                  }
               ],
