                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "Now, we use the same projection and update **Figure 1** to the present day:",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img class=\"imgcenter\" src=\"images/Mapswire/world-physical-map-graticules-mercator-v1_China.jpg\" id=\"imgChina\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgChina', '0%')\"/><b>Figure 3</b>: Mercator projection from the perspective of China (Zhongguo 中國). © Mapswire (<i><htcite0></i>). Compartilhado sob a licença <a href=\"https://whc.unesco.org/en/licenses/6\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 3.0 IGO</a>.</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "dd4f3c8a-6624-4df5-93ac-37e0a4be9fdc",
                     "text": "Mapswire",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: Mapping</b><br /><br />We prefer to present maps without countries, which are human divisions, so that we can reflect in a more natural way. Observing <b>Figures 2 and 3</b>, answer:<br /><br />When we change the position of the continents on the maps, do the colder regions become warmer?<br /><br />Where there was desert, did it become forest?<br /><br />Have you ever stopped to think that, although our species is over 300,000 years old (<htcite0>), the nations we see today are recent?<br /><br />After this movement of the continents between maps, do you see it as a problem to place the region where you live at the center of the map?<br /><br />Did this change in positioning in the figures alter anything in your life?<br /><br />Besides defining the center according to one's own understanding, could some people also claim that humanity emerged where they live, instead of Africa, where it actually emerged?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ab1dda1e-95c2-4087-8299-e851e58bdc6f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Humans",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Conclusion\n\nIn this text, we learned that the definition of a central meridian occurred recently and, even so, it is not unique. Furthermore, we reflected on some scenarios that show that humanity is the same, regardless of where it resides.",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
